She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"You're reading memories?" Ivory asked as she looked at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you go out for Christmas? It's only a few days away."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King would never let her leave, as she was "an error" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in a family otherwise entirely composed of boys.
Ivory was also that way, in her own manner. When she had declared her non-binary identity, it seemed like the world had changed too. She had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude as punishment for her difference.
Iel also had to remain in service to the princess, but that wasn't a big deal since it made her a friend.
"It's soon going to be your birthday, I believe?" Ivory asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming up in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad glint in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As iel asked the question, iel remembered what she had answered last time.
No, Kari gestured with a touch. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she was confined to her room and her mother was banished. When it happened, Ivory was still a baby, but iel remembered the outrage of the servants and the citizens. iel had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... What do you feel like doing?" iel asked. Kari looked up enthusiastically. She handed a piece of paper to Ivory. But when iel glanced at it...
Cloth 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find these things for you?", Ivory said as she turned towards the silent princess who was tapping frenetically, shaking her pigtails back and forth. "Yes?" Iel giggled slightly as she saw the usually reserved princess become passionate about something. It was the first time she had asked for something that wasn't related to books and wasn't found in her room.
"Alright. See you later?", Ivory proposed as she stood up and made her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and wrapped herself back into her thick comforter, sinking back into her memories.
Iel left the room with relief. Finally, the princess was stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that were not within her domain, like paint.
Iel turned back down the halls, trying not to listen to the murmurings of the maids.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, which is why she always goes into that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
Iel covered their ears because trying to ignore it wasn't working. Iel headed towards the royal painter's room, which was on the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door intricately worked just like Kari's. It bore a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, said to have created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to expose it on his door; he loved history.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a typical scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered throughout the room, easels covering every last inch of wall. Surprisingly, iel saw none of that. The room was clean, and there was a red velvet backdrop with a stool right in front. On the stool stood Prince Aquilo, being painted.
"Ah hello, Ivory! Are you here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?"
"Pardon, little prince," he replied, partially ignoring her as he searched for the items his silent friend had desired. "I'm just here to get supplies."
"Ah, is the girl going to leave very soon?" Aquilo asked, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on her list and placed them in a box she had discovered. "And I am not a girl."
However, the prince hadn't thought of that. "Oh my darling, you know it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up," he muttered.
"I have to go," he said suddenly uncomfortable, because of the prince's words which reminded him of the harm people said about his gender identity. I really want to distance myself from him.
"Are you leaving us already?" The Prince appeared at the door right away, ignoring the complaints of the royal painter.
"This is not the behavior of a future king!" he reproached him.
"No one will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he wants to live." He turned back to the painter briefly, then leaned toward Ivory. "What do you think about a gallant rendezvous?" He shuddered. Indeed, iel had received many threats before, but never from a prince, let alone the heir to the throne.
"Do you not know what the word no means?" he retorted, pushing the prince out of his way.
"Heck no," replied Aquilo with a smile. Of course, a prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why want a gallant rendezvous with me rather than with others? You must have a hundred or so suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling broadly: "500, to be exact." He threw back his hair, which flew through the cold air.
"So, why me rather than another? I am the palace's menace." Iel wrapped her arms around his body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
